<tt>Mon Mar 17 23:52:21 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Chet,I have always wondered about the PTSD. Whatever I have is something that I have been fortunate enough to control almost always. I moved from Chicago to Tennessee 25 years ago. I was 23 years old. Just pulled up stakes and vamoosed. Dropped out of society. Was always proud to have done that at such a young age. To just pack up and leave. Of course people thought I was crazy. They may have been at least partially correct.<br><br>
One thing that enabled me to make such a drastic move was my war experience. I remember writing home from RVN and saying that I didn't care what I did with the rest of my life - as long as I made it home. And that is pretty much how I have lived. The experience of Vietnam taught me very much - not the least of which was how to survive.<br><br>
I feel much compassion for the Vietnamese. The men I fought alongside and the men I fought against were courageous. But, I have to say that the peasants, with all of their tenacity, inspired me the most.<br><br>
Who do we look up to in this day and age? The politicians whom we ridicule by force of habit? Are sports heroes really heroes in the true sense of the word? <br><br>
Aren't the best lessons learned by observing those who scratch and claw - each and every day - to make a living? Shouldn't we be inspired by a person's  determination, rather than by his material possessions?<br><br>
The people of Vietnam taught us a great lesson in how to endure in an unbelievably terrible environment.<br>
We shall endure also.<br>

